image.altText: A dim, dark blue picture of a white submersible underwater, with a stream of bubbles coming from it.

items.synopsis: Authorities say the search for the submersible missing near the Titanic wreck is entering a critical stage, with fears the five occupants will run out of oxygen and develop hypothermia if not found soon. Follow live.

title.children: Search intensifies for Titanic sub with only hours of oxygen left

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: As the search for the missing submersible intensifies, here's a recap of what we know so far: If the vessel is still operating, it's estimated to run out of oxygen at around 8pm AEST tonight But, Frank Owen, a former commander in the Royal Australian Navy, says the five crew members could have more time if they've been conserving their oxygen. The experienced French diver on board, Paul-Henri Nargoelet, would be key to directing the other four passengers on how to keep calm and control their breathing, Owen says. The US and Canadian coast guards are still searching an area the size of about 26,000 square kilometres — that's more than twice the size of greater Sydney. The underwater "banging" noises picked up on Tuesday have "yielded negative results" so far, the US coast guard says. We'll continue to keep you updated over the next couple of hours.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Titanic sub crew have around two hours of oxygen left

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: One of the first customers on OceanGate's trips to the Titanic wreckage has characterised his dive to the site as a "kamikaze operation". "You have to be a little bit crazy to do this sort of thing," said Arthur Loibl, a 61-year-old retired businessman and adventurer from Germany. Loibl said he paid $US110,000 (about $162,500) for a dive in 2019 that fell through when the first submersible didn't survive testing. Two years later, he went on a successful voyage along with two men from England, as well as OceanGate chief executive Stockton Rush and French diver Paul-Henri Nargeolet, who are missing on the current voyage. The dive was repeatedly delayed to fix a problem with the battery and the balancing weights, Loibl said. "I was a bit naive, looking back now," he said. Reporting by AP
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Titan dive was a 'kamikaze operation', says one of OceanGate's first customers

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Frank Owen, a former commander in the Royal Australian Navy who directed its submarine escape and rescue project, says the experienced French diver on board the Titan, Paul-Henri Nargeolet, would be instructing the other passengers as to how to conserve oxygen. "He would say lie down, sleep if you can, minimise your movement, do as little as possible and calm yourself down," Mr Owen told the ABC's RN Drive. "So you don't breathe too much and exhale too much CO2. "The 96 hours [of oxygen] is a nominal estimate based on standard consumption [of a certain amount of] litres per minute. If you can reduce that, you can extend your life. "It's not like a parking meter that will click over at 96 and the oxygen will stop."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Kezie Apps takes the first hit-up for NSW.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 1' Queensland kicks off and Origin II is off and running

children.content: Kezie Apps takes the first hit-up for NSW.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: No late changes for either side.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Final teams are locked in

children.content: No late changes for either side.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A two-game series prevents an obvious problem, right? Unlike the men's three-gamers, it's highly likely that there will be drawn series when only two matches are played. So, with Queensland leading 1-0 after their 18-10 win three weeks ago and no reigning series winner to simply retain the shield in the event of a tied series, what happens if the Sky Blues win tonight? Then the winner will be decided by total points scored in the series, which means even if Queensland are trailing late in this game, the fire will still be there to scrap to get over the line or kick a goal to make sure the aggregate is still in the black. If NSW also win 18-10 tonight, leaving both teams even, then we're getting into England in the 2019 Cricket World Cup final-type areas. If the aggregates are even then the countback starts. In descending order: Most tries scored. Most goals kicked. Most drop goals kicked. Least amount of penalties conceded. The team that scored the first try of the series. The team that scored the first goal of the series. The team that scored the first drop goal of the series. And after that I guess they just flip a coin.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: What happens if the Women's Origin series is tied?
